FBIS4-53309 "dreas096_a_94005" FBIS-EAS-94-096 Daily Report 17 May 1994 NORTHEAST ASIA Japan Karimov Supports UNSC Seat for Tokyo Karimov Supports UNSC Seat for Tokyo OW1705142494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1320 GMT 17 May 94 OW1705142494 Tokyo KYODO English BFN [Text] Tokyo, May 17 KYODO -- Uzbekistan President Islam Karimov told Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata on Tuesday [17 May] that his country favors a permanent seat for Japan on the UN Security Council, Foreign Ministry officials said. Karimov said Uzbekistan wishes to see Japan "fulfill the responsibilities" of a permanent Security Council member, the officials said. Hata was quoted as pledging Japanese support for Uzbekistan's efforts to set up a market economy and offered to extend cooperation in economic management. Karimov explained the preparation of legal statutes aimed at attracting foreign investment to the former Soviet republic in Central Asia, the officials said. The two leaders discussed Uzbekistan's potential for exploiting energy and metal resources and the prospect for bilateral cooperation in such fields. Karimov and Hata signed a statement endorsing more political dialogue and confirming that international pacts concluded between Japan and the former Soviet Union remain effective "with the exception of those which cannot meaningfully exist." The statement also said Uzbekistan "expressed the hope that Japan would become a permanent member of the UN Security Council and fulfill its relevant responsibilities."
